uslims. This innovative examination of the discourse and practices surrounding maternity forges new ground as it takes up the historical and epistemic construction of medieval Muslim women's identities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aMotherhoodxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aWomen in Islam. 4aArea Studies : Middle East Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women in Religion. 4aHistory : Medieval Studies. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Islam. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aRELIGION / Islam / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438447872423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438447872/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles